It is a wonderfully odd way to think about it.

A clock doesn’t literally capture time—it captures and displays a regular physical process that we use as a stand-in for time. A pendulum swings, a quartz crystal vibrates, or atoms oscillate at incredibly stable frequencies. We count those repeated events and call the count “time.”

So in one sense:

* A camera captures light.
* A microphone captures sound.
* A clock captures change.

Because change is so tightly linked to our experience of time, it feels like the clock is “capturing time” itself.

There’s a poetic inversion here too: we often say we “don’t have enough time,” yet clocks don’t store any. They simply measure the rate at which the universe unfolds according to a chosen rhythm.

That idea also connects to a deeper observation: if absolutely nothing anywhere changed—no particles moved, no thoughts occurred, no stars burned—would time still be meaningful? Physics and philosophy have debated versions of that question for centuries. Some views treat time as a fundamental ingredient of reality; others see it as something that emerges from change and relationships between events.

So yes—it is a bit silly, and also profound, that we built little machines that seem to “catch time,” when what they’re really catching is the heartbeat of the universe.